{"/service/ndnp/mdu/batch_mdu_frederick_ver03/data/sn89060127/00279522035/1938011401/0020.xml":{"full_text":"Page 4\nWORCESTER DEMOCRAT\naND\nTHE LEDGER-ENTERPRISE\nPublished Every Friday at Pocomoke City, Maryland.\nEDWARD J. CLARKE, Editor and Owner\n$1.60 The Year In Advance.\nEntered at the Postoffice at Pocomoke City, Maryland, as Second Class Matter\nOfo NATIONAL EDITORIAL\njn ASB CIAnor\nFRIDAY, JANUARY 14, 1938\nA NEW FEATURE\nWe would like to call the attention of our readers to our new\nfeature \u2014a weekly magazine section \u2014which appears this week,\nand will continue to do so every other week to all our subscribers,\nand if the reaction to this venture is assuring it will be sent out\nevery week.\nThis periodical, known as \u201cTown,\u201d is a sixteen page paper and\ncontains matter, interesting to almost all our readers, and it goes\nto them without any extra cost in the way of subscripion price.\nIts cover page is illuminated always by some beautiful works\nof art, in the way of landscapes, buildings, personages, and sea\nviews. The reading matter appeals to the home and fireside; the\ntraveller; the sportsman; fiction readers; fashions; and mind teas\ners in the way of puzzles.\nThere are two pages of colored comics; interesting radio news,\nstories of screen artists; lots of recipes fo cooking; many direc\ntions fo first aid in accidents; safe rules for driving\u2014and, in short,\nthere is page after page of week-end perusal which will give all\nour readers pleasure, information, and mental relaxation. If you\nlike it, let us know.\nGROWING CLEAVAGE IN THE PARTIES\nAs the regular session of Congress gets under way, the most\nsignificant political occurrence is the growing cleavage in the ma\njority party. No President enjoyed a longer or more complete\nhoneymoon with Congress than did Mr. Roosevelt\u2014throughout his\nentire first term he faced almost no opposition, and for the first\nyear of his second term the opposition was scattered and ineffect\nual. His leaders in House and Senate experienced little trouble in\nrounding up next-to-unanimous support for White House measures\nand deflecting Congressmen were swiftly and definitely punished.\nToday a different situation obtains, with a substantial part of the\nDemocratic majority in open revolt against Administration objec\nives ,and with a larger part in quiet, tacit revolt. During the lat\nter part of the regular session and the entire special session, the\nmajority leaders worked untirjngly to heal wounds and bring the\ndissenters back into the New Deal fold\u2014and they failed almost;\ncompletely. This was especially noticeable in the Senate, where\nMr. Barkley, successor to Mr. Robinson, met practically as much\nopposition among the members of his own paty as among the Re- 1\npublicans.\nThe open cleavage began with the Supreme Court bill. But\ntrouble had been brewing before, and the introduction of this\nmeasure gave Congressmen who had been growing restive and\ndoubtful of Administration policies the opportunity they had look\ned for to split with the White House. The Black appointment mark\ned another major blow to the President\u2019s power and prestige. By\nOctober, as Mark Sullivan pointed out recently, \u201cit was fair to esti\nmate that the Democrats in Congress opposed to much of Mr.\nRoosevelt\u2019s program, were at least equal in number to those who\nsupported his program.\u201d Today the latter group is probably ac\ntually in the majority. The last important White House \u201cmust\nmeasure\u201d\u2014the .wage and hours bill\u2014typifies the trend. It is no\nsecret that every possible tactic was used in an attempt to get this\nbill through. In July, before the business recession, it passed the\nSenate by a majority of exactly two to one. In December, a simi\nlar bill, changed somewhat in wording but almost identical in pur\npose, was beaten by the House, 216 to 198. And it was the Demo- j\ncrats, not the weak Republican ranks, which beat it.\nSome lecent events have made the split all the more drama\ntically clear. It is a reasonable assumption that the majority of\nthe Democrats in Congress want to help and cooperate with, busi\nness. There is a very strong bloc which wishes to put tax revision\nand friendly industrial legislation first on the calendar. While the\nPresident is not actively opposed to this, his attitude is one of cool\nness, and he apparently believes that such legislation is of minor\nimportance, and should be deferred. Secretary Ickes has made a\nspeech which amounted to a sweeping attack on big business, and\nno one believes a cabinet member would make so vital an address\nwithout the permission of his Chief. In other words, the Admin-,\nistration seems to be bent on going ahead with its program, whose\ncardinal point is the radical revision of American industry, and an\nincreasing measure of government control over business. Many\nleading Democrats are largely opposed to this, and feel that it\nwould very possibly force us into another long depression, great\ner centralization of government with undermining of democratic\ninstitutions. It is over this point that the struggle for control of\nthe Democratic party, between New Dealers on the one hand and\nthe conservative wing on the othr, is now taking place.\nThe elections late this fall will determine the outcome\u2014in the\nprimaries in many places, New Deal Democrats will be opposed to\nAnti-New Deal Democrats, in a frank fight for power. In the\nmeantime, Congress will cotinue to be tom by the opposed schools\nof thought\u2014which means that there will be a great deal more talk\nthan action, and that major legislation is likely to become stale\nmated.\nThe regular session of Congress faces precisely the same prob\nlem that confronted the special session when it met November 15.\nThat problem is, How can the business recession be stopped?\nThe special session reached a new high in non-achievement.\nThere was a great deal of talk concerning ways and means to re\nassure business \u2014and almost no action. If a similar stalemate is\nreached in the present session, the outlook for the future of the\ncountry will be serious indeed.\nThe greatest need of the time is actual cooperation by gov\nernment with industry, which is the sole source of productive em\nployment, investment, spending power and taxation. The first\nstep Congress should take, if it is honestly interested in real na\ntional recovery, is to revise those two \u201ctaxes without a friend\u201d\nwhich have done so much to kill business and investment\u2014the\nundistributed profits tax and the capital gains tax.\nNeither of these taxes is an important revenue producer. They\nactually tend to reduce tax revenues, because of their depressive\neffect on industrial activity. There is a remarkable unanimity of\nopinion among informed persons as to their dangers. Business\nmen. large and small, are solidly opposed to them. Outstanding\neconomists can find nothing to say in their favor. The nation\u2019s\nprincipal newspapers, of all political affiliations, are requesting 1\nthat they be drastically changed. And a large number of public\nofficials, of both parties, have gone on record in favor of revision\nor outright repeal.\nw* HUCKSTER DEMOCRAT, POCOMOKE CITY, MARYLAND\nAccomac News\nMr. and Mrs. Carl J. Junes and\nson, Carl, of Nassawadox spent the\ni week-end with Mrs. Jones parents,\nMr. and Mrs. John I. Burford.\nMiss Hortense E. Kelley of New\nChurch, spent the week-end with Miss\nMay Gunter Edmonds.\nThe Rev. William K. Haddock is\nspending a week in Savannah, Ga.\nMiss Ruth Byrd has returned from\na visit with relatives in Philadelphia.\nMiss Beulah Wessells, of Nassawa\ndox spent the week-end with relatives\nhere.\nMrs. Elson Hornbeck, of Westfield,\nN. J., recently spent several days with\nMr. and Mrs. Phil T. Milliner.\nMrs. William P. Bell is spending\ntwo months in New Orleans, La.\nMr. and Mrs. Elic Kelley, of New\nChurch spent the week-end with Mrs.\nKelley\u2019s parents, Mr. and Mrs. Aimer\nJ. Fox.\nMrs. William K. Haddock and son,;\nKenney are spending a week with'\nrelatives in Richmond.\nMrs. J. H. Ayres and Miss Eliza-j\nbeth Ayres are spending the winter\nin Richmond.\nMr. and Mrs. Aaron S. Byrd and\nMiss Mary Virginia Byrd spent the\npast week-end in Baltimore, Md.\nMr. and Mrs. John W. Burford and\ndaughter, Charlotte Whittington, of\nNewport News, spent the past week\nend with Mr. Burford\u2019s parents, Mr.\nand Mrs. John I. Burford.\nMr. Donald M. Shute of Hampton!\nspent the week-end in the home of j\nMrs. Edgar D. Fletcher.\nMr. Aaron S. Byrd, Jr., of Rich-;\nmond, is spending this week-end with'\nhis parents, Mr. and Mrs. Aaron S.j\nByrd.\nMr. and Mrs. William F. Ayres and\nMr. and Mrs. Marvin Cole of Balti-;\nmore, Md., were called here last week-:\nend by the sudden death of Mr. J. Wes\nley Colebum.\nMiss Edna Melson of Baltimore, Md. j\nis spending two weeks with her par\nents, Mr. and Mrs. George C. Melson. j\nMr. H. T. Coard spent several days 1\nthis week in Philadelphia\nCC C COLDS\nUy D FEVER\nLiquid, Tablets TT f rst day\nSalve, Nose Headache, 30\nDrops minutes\nTry \u201cliub-My-Tism\u201d World\u2019s Best\nLiniment\nAljULiTiTliliTiTtTiTiTiTiTiTuiT*TiTiTaTiTiiiTaTiTtT >ll\nBroadcast\nYour Message\nTHRU\nThe Worcester Democrat\n(Figuring the national average of 5 readers to a paper)\nRead By More Than 15,000 People\nThere\u2019s no stronger advertising med\nium than the newspaper t\u2019s the uni\nversal American habit. Everyone\nwith brains reads. Newspaper ad\nvertising therefore reaches virtually\nall who buy.\nWe are equipped\nto do any kind of\nJOB WORK\nPromptly and\nSatisfactorily\nWorcester Democrat\nPrinters Publishers\nj Pocomoke Phone 236\nMr Kenneth Ilayden is able to be\nout, after having had his tonsils ex\ntracted the first of the week\nt\ni i\nThomas M. Harrington s\nand 11\nJohn S. Whaley\n\nSolicitors\nAssignee\u2019s Sale;\nOF VALUABLE\nFARM PROPERTY\nUnder and by virtue of the Power\nof Sale contained in a mortgage from\nSidney C. Townsend and Susie B.\nTownsend, his wife, dated January 30,\n1934, and recorded among the Land\nRecords of Worcester County, Mary\nland, in Liber B. B. No. 20, folios 524,\n525, 526,627 and 528, which said mort\ngage was duly assigned to the under\nsigned Assignee for the purpose of\nforeclosure and collection, default hav\ning occurred therein, the said under\nj signed Assignee will offer for sale at\nJ public auction to the highest bidder in\nfront of the Parker House in Poco\nmoke City, Worcester County, Mary\nland, on\nSATURDAY FEB., 5,1938\nAt 2:00 O\u2019clock P. M.\nAll that tract of land containing\n85 acres, more or less, situate in the\nFirst Election District, Worcester\nCounty, Maryland, on both sides of a\ncounty road leading from McMaster\nSchool House to Tull\u2019s Mill, about five\nmiles south from Pocomoke. BEING\nall and the same land which was con\nveyed to the said Sidney C. Townsend\ni from William S. Townsend, Executor\n!of the last Will and Testament of\nSidney F. Townsend, deceased, by\ni deed dated January 31, 1918, record\ned among the aforesaid Land Records\nin Liber O. D. C. No. 30, folio 186.\nBEING ALSO all and the same prop\nerty covered by the mortgage first\nherein mentioned, to which deed and\nmortgage reference is hereby made\nfor a more particular description of\nthis land.\nThis farm is suitable for cultivation\nwith crops raised in this County and\nlocality. There are 35 acres suitable\nfor cultivation and the balance pas\nture and wood land. The property is\nI improved by a two-story frame and\nj brick dwelling with one and one-half\n1 story annex, tenant house, barn and\nother outbuildings.\nTERMS OF SALE\nj $500.00 cash at time and place of\nsale, balance upon final ratification\nof said sale by the Circuit Court of\nsaid County. Taxes and other\ncharges adjusted to day of sale. Deed\nand title papers at cost of purchaser.\nJOHN S. WHALEY, Assignee I\nJan. 14-4 t.\nNOTICE\nAll operators of public dance halls, J\nboxing or wrestling arenas and tour\nists\u2019 camps with cabins for hire, out\nside of the incorporated towns in l\nWorcester County, Maryland, must se\ncure permits from the Board of\nCounty Commissioners of Worcester\nCounty in compliance with the Acts\nof the 1937 General Assembly. Appli\ncations for permits may be secured\nfrom the Clerk to tftfc Board of Coun\nty Commissioners at the Court House\nin Snow Hill, Maryland. A fee of\n$1.25 must accompany each applica\ntion. Those operators failing to ob\ntain such a permit by January 20,\n1938 will be subject to a fine of SIOO.-\n00 to $500.00 and the possibility of\nhaving their places of business order\ned closed.\nThe Board of County Commissioners\nof Worcester County, Maryland\nJan. 7-2 t.\nREPORT OF CONDITION OF THE\nPOCOMOKE CITY NAT\u2019L BANK\nof Pocomoke City, in the State of\nMaryland, at the close of bnsiness, on\nDecember 31, 1937.\nPublished in Response to call made\nby Comptroller of the Currency, under\nSection 5211, U. S. Revised Statutes.\nASSETS\nLoans and discounts $287,531.70\nOverdrafts 235.64\nUnited States Government\nobligations, direct and\nor fully guaranteed 327,100.00\nOther bonds, stocks, and se\ncurities 43,591.68\nBanking house, $48,500.00\nFurniture and fix\ntures 4,500 53,000.0\nReal estate owned other\nthan banking house 27,202.00\nReserve with Federal\nReserve Bank 106,165.74\nCash items not in process\nof collection 100,681.68\nAcceptances of other banks\nand bills of exchange or\ndrafts sold with endorse\nment of this bank 761.35\nOther Assets 9,563.11\nTotal Assets $955,832.90\nLIABILITIES\nDemand deposits of indivi\nduals, partnerships and\ncorporations 319,095.01\nTime deposits of indivi\nduals, partnerships and\ncorporations 477,063.24\nState, county and munici\npal deposits 63,768.6\nUnited States Government\nand postal _ savings de\nposits 1,005.33.\nDeposits of other banks,\nincluding certified and\ncashiers\u2019 checks outstand\ning 1,109.21\nDeposits secured by\npledge of loans and or\ninvestments ...45,269.93\nDeposits not secured by\npledge of loans and or\ninvestments .816.771.52\n\nTotal deposits. 862,041.45\nCapital account:\nCommon stock, 5000 shares,\npar, SIO.OO per share\n50,000.00\nSurplus 31,500.00\nUndivided profits\nnet 12,291.45\nTotal Capital Account.... 93,791.45\nTotal Liabilties $955,832.90\nMEMORANDUM: Loans and Invest\nments pledged to secure liabilities\nUnited States Government\nobligations, direct and\nfully guaranteed 36,000.00\nOther bonds, stocks and\nsecurities 9,269.93\nTotal pledged (excluding\nrediscounts) 45,269.9\nPledged:\nAgainst State coun\nty and municipal depos\nits 45,269.93\nTotal Pledged 45,269.9\nState of Maryland, County of Wor\ncester. ss:\nI, Willard J. Stevenson, Cashier of\nthe above-named bank, do solemnl)\nswear that the above statement is tru*\nto the best of my knowledge and be\nlief.\nWILLARD J. STEVENSON, Cashier.\nSworn to and subscribed before me\nthis 6th day of January, 1938.\nMYRA E. MESSICK, N. P\nCorrect\u2014Attest:\nFRANK J. LLOYD,\nELLWOOD E. MATTHEWS\nEUGENE P. MATTHEWS,\nDirectors.\nTo Get Rid of Acid\nand Poisonous Waste\nYour kidneys help to keep yon well\nby constantly filtering waste matter\nfrom the blood. If your kidneys get\nfunctionally disordered and fail to\nremove excess impurities, there may be\npoisoning of the whole system and\nbody-wide distress.\nBurning, scanty or too frequent uri\nnation may be a warning of some kidney\nor bladder disturbance.\nYou may suffer nagging backache,\npersistent headache, attacks of dizziness,\ngetting up nights, swelling,' puffiness\nunder the eyes\u2014 feel weak, nervous, all\nplsyed out.\nIn such cases it is better to rely on a\nmedicine that has won country-wide\nReclaim loan on something less favor\nably known. Use Poem's Pills. A multi-\nS t'uJf- if grateful people recommend\nk r )r,i i s. Ask your t.risjhbor'.\nWe have one of the finest equipped\nplants oo Lie Shore for turning out\niimn class pv.nung.\nCARD OF THANKS\nWe want to express our deep apprecia\ntion to the Pocomoke Firemen and\nothers who labored so tirelessly to i\nsave our home. It was a splendid,\npiece of work, and we will ever be\ndeeply grateful.\nThe lovely expressions of sympathy\nfrom our nighbors and friends will al\nso be ever gratefully remembered.\nMrs. Minnie Hall and children\nJan. 14-ltp.\nL. Paul Ewell, Solicitor\nMortgage Foreclosure\noi\nRestaurant and\nHotel Property\non Willow Street,\nPocomoke City, Md.\nUnder and by virtue of the power of\nsale contained in a mortgage from\nJohn W. Reid and Katherine D. Reid,\nhis wife, to John Edwin Powell, same\n1 bearing date August 31, 1929, and re\ncorded among the land records of\nWorcester County, Maryland, in Liber\nB. B. No. 8, folios 133, etc., the under\nsigned trustee named therein for fore\nclosure, will offer for sale at public\nauction on\nSat., January 29, 1938\nAt the hour of Three o\u2019clock in the\n1 afternoon\nIn front of the Parker House,\nPocomoke City, Md.\nAll that lot or parcel of ground sit\nuate, lying and being in Pocomoke\nCity, Worcester County, Maryland, on\nthe southwest side of Willow Street,\ni having a width on said Willow Street\nof 47 feet and a depth of 80 feet,\nI adjoining the property of L. Paul\nEwell on the northwest, the Armory\nof the Maryland National Guard on\nthe southwest and the property for-\nI I merly owned by Cornelia Davis and an\nalley on the southeast, being all and\nthe same property conveyed by the\nmortgage aforesaid, and also all and\nthe same property conveyed to the\nsaid John W. Reid and Katherine D.\nReid, as tenants by the entireties,;\nfrom the said John Edwin Powell and\nj wife by deed dated August 29, 1929,\nj and recorded among the land records\n|of Worcester County, Maryland, in\nLiber B. B. No. 7, folios 401, etc.,\ntogether with the buildings and im\nprovements thereon and all the alleys\nand ways thereto belonging or in\nanywise appertaining.\nThis property has the use in com-!\n'j mon with other owners and occupiers!\nof an alley fourteen feet in width\nrunning northwesterly from Second j\nStreet along the Davis property and\n'also a strip fourteen feet in width ex- 1\ntending from the Armory property to\nthe Davis property, this strip being\nabout twenty-eight feet from said Ar\nmory property to said Davis proper\nty. This property is improved by a\nbrick and concrete restaurant and\nhotel building and is commonly called\n\u201cReid\u2019s Hotel and Restaurant.\u201d It is\nwell located and should be of interest\nto anyone desiring a good business\nproperty. There are twelve bed\nrooms.\nTerms of sale CASH.\nTitle papers and revenue tax at the\nexpense of the purchaser. Taxes paid\n\u201eto January 1, 1938. Possession on\nratification of sale.\nL. PAUL EWELL, Trustee\nJan. 7-4 t.\nGodfrey Child, Solicitor\nPocomoke City, Md.\nIn the matter of the Petition of\n1 William James Messick, Jr., for the\nchange of his name to William Mes\nsick Purnell\nIn the Circuit Court for Worcester\nCounty, Maryland.\nIn Equity.\nNo. 4895 Chancery.\nORDER NISI\nA petition having been filed in the\nabove entitled cause by William James\nMessick, Junior, of Ocean City, Wor\ncester County, Maryland, praying for\na decree changing his name to William\nMessick Purnell,\nIt is thereupon, this twenty-ninth\nday of December, 1937, ordered by\nthe Circuit Court for Worcester\nCounty, Maryland, sitting in Equity,\nthat the name of William James Mes\nsick, Junior, be changed to William\nMessick Purnell by a final order and\ndecree in this Court, unless cause to\nthe contrary thereof be shown on or\nbefore the seventeenth day of January,\n1938, provided a copy of this order\nbe inserted in some weekly newspaper\nprinted and published in Worcester\nCounty, Maryland, once in each of\nthree successive weeks before the fif\nteenth day of January, 1938.\nJAMES M. CROCKETT, Judge.\nTrue Copy, Test: Bessie Bowen, Clerk\nDec. 30-3 t.\nWilson K. Barnes, Attorney\nNOTICE TO CREDITORS\nNotice is hereby given that the\nsubscriber has obtained from the Or\nphans\u2019 Court for Worcester County,\nMaryland, letters Testamentary on the\npersonal estate of Ella Wilson Led\nnum, formerly Ella M. Wilson, late of\nWorcester County, deceased.\nAll persons having claims against\nthe deceased, are hereby warned to\nexhibit the same, with the vouchers\nthereof, to the subscriber on or be\nfore the 4th day of July, 1938. They\nmay otherwise by law be excluded\nfrom all benefits of the said estate.\nAll persons indebted to said estate\nare requested to make immediate pay\nment. Given under my hand this 23rd\nday of December, 1937.\nWilson K. Executor.!\nTest: Paul Jones, Register of Wills.!\nDec. 23-4 t.\nFriday, January 14, 1938\nClassified Advertisin g\nNOTICE\u2014A hog came to my\nFriday, January 7. Owner may have\nsame by proving ownership and pay\ning expenses incurred. E. L. Mi\nboume, Route 2.\nJan. 14-ltp.\nWANTED\nWORK WANTED\u2014Practical mus\ning or position as companion to elder\nly person. Call Worcester Democrat.\nJan. 14-2tp.\nSALESMAN we*\nknown oil company. Man over thirty\npreferred. Experience not necessary.\nImmediate steady income for mas\nwith car. Write P. T. Webster, s\u00aet\nStandard Building, Cleveland, Ohio.\nJan. 14-ltp.\nWANTED\u20144 men want work os\nfarm at once. Thomas Watson, Gresa\nbush, Va.\nJan. 14-ltp.\nFRESH SAUSAGE\u20142Sc lb. in 5\nlots. Call Pocomoke 3 F 14.\nJan. 14-lt.\nWANTED\u2014Man to tend farm on\nshares. Will furnish house, team and\nmachinery. Farm situated between\nGirdletree and Stockton. Mrs. S. J.\nMatthews, Girdletree, Md.\nJan. 7-3 t.\nFOR SALE\nFOR SALE\u2014Frying chickens,\nweighing 2 to 3 lbs. Mrs. Charles\nChesser.\nJan. 14-2 t.\nFOR SALE\u2014Pigs. Mrs. Josephine\nPolk, Phone 2 F 3.\nJan. 7-2tp.\nTWO STORAGE ROOMS FOR\nRENT\u2014I. H. Merrill Co.\nDec. 30-tf.\nFOR SALE\u2014Estate Oil Heatrola,\n7000 cubic feet capacity, used less\nthan one month. Eastern Shore Gas\nCorporation.\nDec. 30-tf.\nFOR SALE\u2014A large assortment of\nused Oil and Gasoline Stoves at bar\ngain prices. Eastern Shore Gas Co.,\nPocomoke 12-2-tf\nFOR RENT\nFOR RENT\u20146-room house, 90J.'\nSecond St. Modem conveniences. J.\nM. Custis.\nDec. 23-tf.\nFOR RENT\u2014House at 911 Clarke\nAvenue, water lights, and bath. Apply\nto William H. Merrill.\nDec. 23-tf.\n5-ROOM APARTMENT FOR RENT\nLights and bath. Henrietta Chatham.\nSept. 24-tf.\nMISCELLANEOUS\nHAULING OF ALL KlNDS\u2014Spec\nial low prices. Francis E. Young,\nPocomoke, Route 1. Phone 326-W.\nJan 14-4 t.\nANNOUNCEMENT\u2014I have moved\nmy sewing room from the Callahan\nBuilding to my home, 604 Second St.,\nand am equipped to do all kinds o l\nsewing. Mrs. Eva S. Tull.\nJan. 7-tf.\nDR. G. E. FlNNEY\u2014Graduate Lic\nensed Veterinarian. Onancock, Va.\nPhone 168. Aug.-27-tf\nFeet Hurt? Groh\u2019s Sponge Rubbcs\nArch Supports relieves tired aching\ncalloused feet. For comfort Phone\n128 W or write, Mr. Groh.\nMarch 19-tf.\nNOTICE\u2014Price on hair cutting\n-25 cents will remain the same at\nShaws.\nJuly 10-tf\nNOTICE TO CREDITORS\nNotice is hereby given that the sub\nscribers have obtained from the Or\nphans\u2019 Court for Worcester County,\nMaryland, letters of Administration\non the personal estate of A. Hartley\nStevens, Sr., late of Worcester County,\ndeceased.\nAll persons having claims against\nthe deceased, are hereby warned to\nexhibit the same, with the vouchers\nthereof, to the subscriber on or be\nfore the 11th day of July, 1938. They\nmay otherwise by law be excluded\nfrom all benefits of the said estate.\nAll persons indebted to said estate are\nrequested to make immediate pay\nment. Given under my hand this 30th\nday of December, 1937.\nW. SIDNEY STEVENS,\nJOHN H. STEVENS,\nA. HARTLEY STEVENS,\nJr.\nAdministrators\nTest: Paul Jones, Register of Wills.\nDec. 30-4 t.\nNOTICE TO CREDITORS\nNotice is hereby given that the sub\nscriber has obtained from the Or\nphans\u2019 Court for Worcester County,\nMaryland, letters of Administration\non the personal estate of Weltha\nMason, late of Worcester County, de\nceased.\nAll persons having claims against\nthe deceased, are hereby warned to ex\nhibit the same, with the vouchers\nthereof, to the subscriber on or before\nthe 18th day of July, 1938. They may\notherwise by law be excluded from all\nbenefits of.the said estate. All per\nsons indebted to said estate are re\nquested to make immediate payment.\nGiven under my hand this 6th day of\nJanuary. 1938.\nJENNIE V. LAMBERTSON\nAdministratrix\nTest: Paul Jones, Register of Wills.\nJan 7-ot.","height":"25158","width":"20439"}}
